            p We know that navigating the world of website localization can raise a lot of questions. To make things easier, we've built a comprehensive FAQ section. 
            p Here, you'll find answers to the most common questions we receive about our services.
            br
            h3 How to translate a whole website?
            p To translate the whole website, integrate i18next with Locize for efficient internationalization. Start by setting up i18next in your React project and create JSON files for each language. 
            p Use Locize as a translation management platform to store and manage these translations, which will automatically sync with your app. 
            p Replace static text in your components with the t function from i18next to dynamically pull translations. This approach allows for scalable, easy-to-manage translations across your website. 
            p Simply follow our <a href="https://docs.locize.com/integration/getting-started" title="getting started guide">getting started guide</a> to see how easy it is to start with Locize.
            br
            h3 How much does website translation cost?
            p To adequately answer this question, you must first determine who is translating and localizing your project. For example, most agencies charge around $0.20 per word for professional human translation services. On the other hand, hiring a freelancer for website translation can cost as little as $0.10 per word. But this is just translating words and no translation management at all.
            br
            p So to automate also the <a href="https://locize.com/" title="translation management">translation management</a> use Locize as translation management system. <b>For the first 10,000 words, Locize charges roughly $0.004</b>. 
            p Website localization is more than just translating words. You can find a detailed breakdown of our costs under <a href="#pricing" title="pricing">pricing</a>. Using a service like Locize is a great way to save time and money on your translation projects.
            
              

